      <hedline>
        <hl1>Experiences Vary Widely For Biracial Children</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael A White letter recalls bittersweet memories prompted by Felicia R Lee's April 30 article on interracial families (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Felicia R. Lee's cover article on interracial families, ''Bridging a Divide'' (April 30), brought back bittersweet memories. My black father's parents were children of slaves, and my Italian mother's parents were immigrants from Genova and Palermo. They married in 1950 and had five sons.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Felicia R. Lee's cover article on interracial families, ''Bridging a Divide'' (April 30), brought back bittersweet memories. My black father's parents were children of slaves, and my Italian mother's parents were immigrants from Genova and Palermo. They married in 1950 and had five sons.</p>
        <p>Times change, but conditions remain the same. White America will never accept children of biracial unions into their fold. We are children created out of our parents' love but racial prejudice has a cold heart. We will always have to overachieve to be granted the rights that children of white parents are given as their birthrights.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL A. WHITE  Flatbush, Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
